# Cue Animation Default

When adding or changing animation in Flutter UI, prefer the `cue` package over hand-wired `AnimationController` code, ad-hoc implicit animations, or one-off animation wrappers.

## Use Cue For

- coordinated entrance/exit scenes
- hover, toggle, focus, and scroll-driven motion
- staggered child animations
- reusable motion patterns that should stay consistent
- page/detail/modal transitions that need polish beyond a simple one-off fade

## Default Pattern

- one `Cue` high enough to own the scene trigger
- `Actor` for each animated child or delay group
- shorthand acts like `.fadeIn()`, `.slideY()`, `.scale()`
- explicit `motion:` on the `Cue`
- stagger with `Actor.delay`, not multiple separate triggers

## Don’t Reach For Cue

- no-motion layout changes
- trivial built-in Material interactions already covered by core widgets
- animation-free state management or routing work

## Project Guidance

- Read `.agents/skills/cue-animations/SKILL.md` before implementing non-trivial animation work
- Prefer Cue for new animation systems instead of wiring imperative controllers manually
- Keep animation reusable: if a motion pattern appears in multiple places, extract it into a shared widget or scene pattern
